,"1130":"1130","1160":"1160","1070":"1070","1107":"1107","1105":"1105","1104":"1104","1178":"1178","1133":"1133","1155":"1155","about 1104":"about 1104","about 1130":"about 1130","Clayton, Lancashire, England":"Clayton, Lancashire, England","Dol-de-Bretagne, Ille-et-Vilaine, Brittany, France":"Dol-de-Bretagne, Ille-et-Vilaine, Brittany, France","Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Lanarkshire, Scotland","Kilmarnock Castle, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Scotland","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Longsworth","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Longworth  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Longworth","meanings":["English: habitational name from Longworth in Bolton le Moors, Lancashire. The placename derives from Old English <i>lang</i> ‘long’ + <i>worth</i> ‘enclosure’."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert De Longsworth was born about 1104, in Dol-de-Bretagne, Ille-et-Vilaine, Brittany, France, his father, Rainald De Holland, was 35 and his mother, De Holland, was 26. He had at least 3 sons with Eschina De Londoniis of Molle. He died in 1160, in Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 57."},"et":{"about 1104–1160":"umbes 1104–1160","1099–Male":"1099–Surnud","1104–1160":"1104–1160","1107–1186":"1107–1186","1105–Female":"1105–Surnud","1130–1163":"1130–1163","1133–1178":"1133–1178","1155–1240":"1155–1240","1070–Male":"1070–Surnud","1080–Female":"1080–Surnud","1080":"1080","1099":"1099","1186":"1186","1240":"1240","1163":"1163","1130":"1130","1160":"1160","1070":"1070","1107":"1107","1105":"1105","1104":"1104","1178":"1178","1133":"1133","1155":"1155","about 1104":"umbes 1104","about 1130":"umbes 1130","Clayton, Lancashire, England":"Clayton, Lancashire, England","Dol-de-Bretagne, Ille-et-Vilaine, Brittany, France":"Dol-de-Bretagne, Ille-et-Vilaine, Bretagne, Prantsusmaa","Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Lanarkshire, Scotland","Kilmarnock Castle, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Scotland","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1104–1160":"noin 1104–1160","1099–Male":"1099–Kuollut","1104–1160":"1104–1160","1107–1186":"1107–1186","1105–Female":"1105–Kuollut","1130–1163":"1130–1163","1133–1178":"1133–1178"